SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received my second dose of the COVID 19 Moderna vaccine on Tuesday morning. By Tuesday night I started to have virtually every side effect that Moderna listed including; fatigue, headache, muscle pain, joint pain, chills, nausea and vomiting, and extreme fever. The next morning as I woke up in attempt tp get ready for work, I was not feeling any better and began to feel light headed, and felt the need to vomit. As I had the feeling of needing to vomit, I turned to do so and fainted. From accounts by my family, I was told I woke up, and quickly passed out a second time. As I was awoken, there was probably a minute before I fainted for a third time. All three times I was told I lost consciousness. I was awoken and by that point my family had contacted emergency responders. Paramedics arrived and took all necessary vitals. I did not pass out after that third time. As I expected all side effects Moderna listed, I did not expect to feel as bad as I did and I thought it was worth reporting what happened to be the next day. It caused a panic and I was scared and nervous as I was unsure why that was happening. I've tried to look up articles and links between passing out and the vaccine and all I can find is people fainting as they get the vaccine (which is common for any shot) but nothing for fainting that long after the vaccine was administered. I just wanted to report my incident.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Felt like she was going to pass out; Dizziness; She couldn't function properly; Felt cross eyed; Dull headache; Shoulder pain at injection site; Chills; Fever; A spontaneous report was received from  a customer concerning a 26-year old female patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced vaccination site pain, chills, fever, dizziness, dull headache, feeling cross eyed, inability to function properly, and feeling like she was going to pass out.   The patient's past medical history included migraine and gastritis. Concomitant medication included migraine medication: imitrex, sumatriptan and meclavine.  On 24-DEC-2020, prior to the onset of the events, the patient received a dose mRNA-1273 (lot/batch or dose number not reported) intramuscularly on the right arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.   On 24-DEC-2020, the patient experienced shoulder pain at injection site, chills and fever that evening. On 25-DEC-2020, the right arm was still hurting. On 26-DEC-2020, she had dizziness, a dull headache felt cross eyed and felt that she couldn't function properly. The headache increased intensity making her to go to the hospital on 01-JAN-2021. She felt like she was going to pass out. Information about whether or not she was admitted was not provided.  Laboratory reports were not provided. Treatment information included taking her migraine medications and going to the hospital.   Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not reported.   The outcome of the events was unknown.; Sender's Comments: Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I am a board certified physician in gastroenterology and internal medicine and work for the Medical Center.  I have no hearing or ear history.  Received Pfizer vaccine from work on 12/21/20 L arm IM, no side effects, sore arm for < 24 hours, second dose 1/11/21 L arm IM, no side effects, sore arm for < 24, however, on 1/22/21 work up with muffled hearing and bringing in the left ear only.  Called colleague Doctor who started prednisone 50 mg immediately on 1/23/21 and continued for 4 weeks without improvement.  Audiometry testing 1/25/21 demonstrated moderate high-frequency hearing loss suggestive of sudden sensorineural hearing loss (SSHL).  Emergent CT head and MRI brain and ear were unrevealing.  20 session of hyperbaric oxygen therapy from 1/21-2/21 without substantial improvement.  Vasculitis workup negative with normal ANA, CRP, ESR, ANCA, CBC, CMP.   3/21 COVID-19 antibodies test for exposure negative.  4/21 noting more public event reporting of hearing loss and tinnitus associated with vaccines. reports-grow-amid-covid-19-vaccinations/) while I understand there is not causal evidence yet linked, I feel that there is a temporal relationship and odd correlation that needs to be recorded and accounted prospectively further.  Vascular surgeon, Hematologist who are treating me for a PE and DVT post ankle fracture and surgery do not correlate the SSHL with my DVT, PE, or anticoagulation.  To date 3 audiometry tests demonstrate persistent left-sided moderate high-frequency hearing loss.

Day of vaccination: fine until approx 11:30 pm. I developed a hot/itchy rash on legs followed by a fever of 103, checked with a digital thermometer, and an intense headache. The headache was the worst I?ve ever had and both the headache and fever lasted until the next day. The next day I slept on and off with a 103 fever until 1pm when I finally took Tylenol. The fever and headache slightly receded to about 100 for about 3 hours and then came back and rose to 104. I took more Tylenol and it receded again and came back again. I took two more Tylenol before bed. The next morning I woke up at 7 am and luckily my fever had dropped to 100 and below and I no longer felt the need to take my temp. However my entire upper body felt as though I was in a car accident and had severe whiplash. My neck and head were so painful I couldn?t move them and the arm that I had received the injection was hot and very painful. My other arm was also sore but not as bad and both my hands hurt. My left armpit and a spot under my jaw on the left were also very swollen and painful. I spent the day either unable to move or in tears pacing because the pain was so bad. I periodically took 600 ml of ibuprofen to help alleviate the pain which I think helped a little. I applied an ice pack to my neck and heat pad to the top of my head and rotated a third ice pack between my hands, under my jaw and in my armpit. It was the most severe body pain I?ve ever felt. This lasted until I went to bed. The third day most of the intense pain from the day before was gone but I still had a pretty intense headache and serious stiffness in my neck and head. Which progressively became more intense throughout the day. I continued to use ice and heat and take Tylenol. This pain lasted and increased until going to bed.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I woke up at approx. 2:30 am the next morning with my mouth (tongue and lips),  eyes, and inside of nose on fire, as if dipped in hot sauce.  Anywhere I touched burned.  It felt like it was coming out of my pores, and I jumped into the shower to rinse off, spreading "it" everywhere.  The redness and blisters would migrate every hour or so.  One minute it was my tongue, then it would show up on my chest.  I called the advice nurse who instructed me to take a Benedryl.  My tongue and throat were tingling.  The Benedryl helped, and I was able to go back to bed but woke up four hours later worse than before.  I called again and my PCP was alerted. via email.  She prescribed a run of Prednisone and that stopped it, however after the run was over, it started again.  A second run of Prednisone was taken.  Upon completion, my throat started to tingle again, then stopped.  I have pictures of the hives, swelling, and blisters on my tongue, lips, eye, and chest,   I cannot take the second dose, per PCP.
LAB_DATA: No tests were run, just a review of the pictures via image viewer.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received shot at 2:45 PM on April 2nd. Took 2 Tylenol at 10:15 PM when I went to bed in anticipation that I may wake up not feeling well (I was already starting to feel some malaise).  Woke up around 2:15 AM on April 3 with chills and took temp. It was around 101. I couldnt quote take more Tylenol yet. It continued to rise for the next hour until around 3:00 when it hit 102.7 and 103.2. Took 1 Tylenol at 3:05 and waited to take another one as soon as my 6 hrs was up. So I took the second one at 4:16. Fever went back down to 101.6 in right ear and 102.4 in left ear around 5:10 AM. Fever as of 5:55 AM is down to 101, however that is still with Tylenol in my system. Even when temp was at 103 I still had Tylenol on system. I am surprised given I have an immune deficiency that my reaction so far has been this strong. Early on with the very high fever I had uncomfortable shaking. Now at 5:57 I am chilled but also sweating. I still have a fever even with Tylenol in my system.

On April 1, 2021 I got my first dose of the COVID-19 EUA vaccination at  (Moderna, lot number: 028A21A) around 7pm (although my appointment was at 5:15pm but that's a whole different story about capitalism's inefficiency. About 30 mins after the vaccination I started getting a headache that turned into a migraine within the hour and did not respond to over the counter treatments (alieve, excedrine) nor did it respond to my second course treatments from the neurologist (as I get chronic migraines), such as triptans (imitrex, and today I tried amerge). I just wanted to report these symptoms to a) increase awareness of negative side effects in populations of the chronically ill and b) provide information that could alter the vaccination's preparation so others may not have to suffer the same side effects in the future.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After the first vaccine on 2/6/2021,  I did not have any reaction except a sore arm until 2/10/2021 when developed a bad headache causing me to leave work.  When I awoke on 2/11/21 I felt worse as the day went on until I had complete flu like symptoms.  On Friday, 2/12, I went to my primary care doctor and they did a COVID-19 test which was negative.  Hence, I just waited for the reaction to go away,  I was not better and able to resume normal activity until 2/15/21.  I did decide to get the second shot as I was not entirely sure it was a result of the vaccine. On 2/27/2021, I received the second vaccination.  Again, the immediate side effect was only a sore arm. On the following Monday (3/1/2021) see cont.I began to have what I thought was muscle aches and pains around the mid section on my body but they were manageable.  On Tuesday and Wednesday (3/3/2021) the pain and area of the pain spread and intensified.  I was unable to sleep or find a comfortable position and was losing strength and knew I needed medical attention as I was afraid it was a heart issue.  My husband took me to the ER (3/4/2021).  The ER doctor ran a CT scan with contrast and the result was a blood clot in my right lung and pneumonia in my left lung along with pleurisy. I was then admitted to Clinic on 3/4/2021.  I remained in the hospital until 3/7/2021.  There I was treated with IV antibiotics, warfarin, Lovenox (80mg), and pain medication for the pleurisy. I was also on a full time heart monitor and my heart was checked several times. Since returning home, I finished a dose of two antibiotics and am using an inhaler to help with breathing.  I have also just finished a long dose of steriods.  My INR is still not regulated to the therapeutic level.  Prior to this reaction, I was in the therapeutic range and had been checked.  As of 4/3/2021 I am at 1.8 not in the 2-3 range and have increased my dose from before the reaction at 7.5 mg to 9.0 mg daily.

I have an odd mild taste of metal in my mouth.  My symptoms aren?t concerning enough to seek medical attention as I feel they are just side effects and will go away shortly. Friday April 2, it got worse to where I did not even want to move it and could not reach my arm past my side to reach around and sleeping that night was horrible. Got the shot around 6:40PM on 3/26.  Woke up with severe headache at 6:30AM on 3/26.  By 9:30AM had a temperature of 101 which increased to over 102 within an hour or two.  Experienced nausea and fatigue.  On 3/27, headache continued, fever was over 101.  Arm had redness around injection area and became swollen.  Arm slightly sore, but not bad.  3/28  had low grade temperature in the morning, but it went up to 101 at night.  3/29-present have had a low grade temperature which sometimes went up over 100, but most of the time was around 99.9.  Arm redness worsened on 3/28 (spread over larger area) and continued to get worse over next few days, including becoming very swollen and itching a bit (very mild itch). Swelling started going down on 3/30 and by 4/1 was mostly gone, as was redness.  Arm more or less normal by 4/2, though slight blotchiness around injection shot. Fatigue and headache, sometimes severe, ongoing.  I am prone to migraines, so possibly that this is a migraine that may or may not be related to the injection.  Have experienced mild vertigo from about 3/30 through the present.  Sensation of pressure on head (weigh on top of head or squeezing), accompanied by feeling of motion coming to an abrupt stop when I turn my head (like slamming on the brakes in a speeding car).  I used cold compress and exercise for arm, when it was painful the first few days (much less painful than with first shot, fairly mild), and cold compress on head for the headache.  Still experiencing fatigue.  Tempreature today is down to 99.3.
LAB_DATA: Have not sought medical treatment because it seemed unnecessary, but thought I should let you know.
HISTORY: Eczema (atopic dermatitis), allergies (seasonal and to animals), diagnosed with vestibular migraines in the past few years
ALLERGIES: Erythromycin, bacitracin, propylene glycol, benzyl alcohol (balsam of Peru); lanolin

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt had second Moderna vaccine around 1100.  Because he had dizziness with the last vaccine it was requested that he wait 30 minutes.  At the end of the 30 minutes the patient complained of severe dizziness.  He also had nausea but stated that this was present prior to the vaccine.  The patient was pale and sweaty.  He denied any chest pain or difficulties breathing.  Attempted to get vital signs.  O2 was 96 on room air.  HR was 52.  Unable to get a blood pressure as the patient would not keep his arm straight.  Rapid responders were called to assist and a wheelchair was brought over.  When we were going to move the patient to the wheelchair he complained of even more dizziness so we did not move him.  He declined any juice due to nausea.  He was given a few sips of water and a cold pack was placed on his neck.  Urgent triage responded and attempted to get vital signs as well.  Manual blood pressure was 80/62, HR 47, O2 97% on room air, respiratory rate 14.  Patient denied diabetes or blood sugar issues.  He had eaten breakfast and took all of his normal medications.  First responders then moved patient to the gurney to take him to ER.

About a week after receiving the shot a set of spots appeared on my ankles, and over the next week or so grew more numerous and spread to my feet, with numerous blisters appearing.  The area around the spots gets painful in the evenings.  After a doctor's visit, leading to blood tests and a biopsy, I was diagnosed with IgA vasculitis.   My understanding is that IgA vasculitis can be associated with a reaction to vaccines, although to my knowledge it has not yet been reported in connection with a COVID-19 vaccine.  My doctor advised, "IgA vasculitis has not been reported so far with the Covid vaccine that I could find in the literature.  It has been reported in association with Covid infection and some other vaccines though, so it stands to reason that it may be related."   The symptoms have not yet abated as I am still in the 14-day window after my second vaccination shot, and my doctors have advised to hold off on taking immunosuppressant steroids until that time period elapses.
LAB_DATA: Blood tests and biopsy, leading to a diagnosis of IgA vasculitis as described above.  The biopsy was taken on March 24 and I received  the result on March 31.  A urine test was administered on  March 22 and showed no kidney issues.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is a 16-year-old, male with no known medical history. At 2:48 pm, the patient received a dose of the Janssen vaccine, (lot number 1808980, expires on 06/20/2021) on left deltoid, given by RN. RN confirmed the name and date of birth of patient, but reportedly forgot to check the patient's age. Patient left to EMT waiting area while his mother stayed with RN to edit her vaccination card. At 2:49 pm, the patient's mother reportedly stated "I'm so glad he just turned 16 so he can get the vaccine!" RN l immediately notified RN of situation. RN asked the patient how he was feeling at 2:51, to which his response was "fine". Patient presented via hand off from RN to EMT at 2:55 pm. At 3:00 pm, EMT, began to monitor the patient's vitals, which are as follows: HR 75 BPM, 118 systolic BP, 3 second capillary refill. Patient presented GCS 15, no symptoms of allergic reaction. Skin was pink and dry. Patient was sitting upright and breathing adequately with no difficulty. Patient reports feeling "fine" at 3:00 pm. At 3:05 pm the patient's vitals were: 128 systolic BP. At 3:10 pm the patient's BP was 128/100. At 3:15 pm the patient's  systolic BP was 122. At 3:20 pm the patient's systolic BP was 124. At 3:25 pm the patient's BP was 122/82 with a HR of 58 BPM. Throughout the 30 minute observation period, the patient and his mother were provided with education on the contraindication of Janssen vaccine and children under the age of 16. The patient's mother verbalized understanding of teaching and stated she would follow up with patient's PCP. The patient and his mother left the facility at 3:33 pm. The patient's gait was steady and balanced. The patient was driven home by his mother shortly after leaving the facility.

Earlier today, a Moderna patient at 3213 experienced a 15-30 second seizure after receiving his 1st Moderna vaccine. Shortly after sitting down for his 15-minute post immunization observation period, patient X began seizing resulting in him falling to the ground from a seated position to his left side and seizing for about 15-20 seconds. Patient was positioned in a left lateral recumbent position. Code white was called and EMT arrived on site within 10 minutes.   Patient's immunization questionnaire did NOT have any contraindications that would warrant he should not receive the vaccine. Patient reported no allergies to medications/past immunizations/foods and reported no seizure and/or neurological condition.   Once recovered and at baseline, patient reported having a light breakfast this morning and also having a needle phobia that may have played a role in his adverse response.   Shortly after recovering, patient was coherent and aware of person, place, and time. He remained weak and fatigue and BP readings from EMT indicated hypotension. EKG was normal.   Patient's mother happened to be waiting outside in the car. One of my associates was able to call her in and we updated here on the event.   EMT recommended, and patient agreed, to be taken to the hospital for further examination.

I received the 2nd Moderna vaccination on 3/25/21.  I woke up at 4 am on 3/26/21 with extreme chills & weakness.  I couldn't get warm.  I finally managed to get out of bed.  I turned up the heat, put extra layers of clothes on & lay on the couch with 3 blankets & I still couldn't get warm.  Later when I sat up, I used a heating pad too.  I spent the day going from couch to bed, battling the chills.  At 4 PM that day, I checked my temperature & it was 99.8 F.  My normal temperature is around 97.  My arm was red & very warm.  The area of redness covered my bicep.  Tender to touch & sore.  The chills went away on the 3rd day, but the redness was there for a week, gradually fading to pink.  Today it is gone.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is a * year old * who received a single dose of J&J COVID 19 vaccine in the right deltoid.  Immediately following administration of the vaccine, patient began experiencing the sensation of heart racing, difficulty breathing, and feelings of anxiety.  Patient relates this has happened with vaccines received in the past, as she has postural orthostatic tachycardic syndrome (POTS).  She feels as if this is an aggravation of her POTS.  Patient states she has allergies/sensitivities to ciprofloxacin, bactrim, and sulfa drugs, but she has never needed to use epinephrine.  She denies chest pain/tightness, wheezing, swelling of the face/lips/mouth/tongue/throat, skin rash/itching, cramping abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting.  She does not take any medications on a daily basis.  POTS aggravation.  Patient was not displaying active signs and symptoms of anaphylaxis.  Patient?s heart rate and breathing continued to slow down once patient was brought to a quiet place and started to enact breathing techniques.  Vital signs continued to improve as patient sat.  Patient encouraged to consult her PCP and inform them of their post-vaccination reaction.  She was instructed to go to the emergency department if she should develop chest pain, difficulty breathing, swelling of the face/lips/airway, cramping abdominal pain with nausea and vomiting.   Patient discharged to home
PRIOR_VAX: POTS aggravation

Tested positive for COVID-19 January 11th 2021. Feb 26th 2021 went in to get the first COVID vaccine around 1130 with Public Health. COVID vaccine manufacturer was Moderna. Given in the left deltoid, IM. Patient did stay an extra 30 minutes post vaccine b/c she has lots of allergies. About an hour After the vaccine she experienced pain in her left arm and up into her neck on the left side. Symptoms are very simulair to something that she ingested and had an allergic reaction to in the past. Felt okay the first day, second day (2-27-2021) she had chills, fatigue, aches and pains. Started to feel like she was improving on Monday around the 28th of February 2021. Fever was down.  Still felt fatigued. Nose felt like it was runnng, itching. Experienced dry eyes, started using the eye drops more frequently. Ear canals were itching. She noticed a tickle in her throat later. Not conscious of everything all the same time, she just didn't feel well overall. Vagina and anus were itching. Started to use the estradiol compound daily hoping that might help. Itchy all over and then realized that the reaction was sort of the same reaction she had in the past with the statin medication. Few days after that had abdominal bloating and cramping, also loose stool and finally diarrhea. Around that same time she reports that she was very dizzy and saw stars, had to sit down, did not actually faint. Denies any fainting episodes, but felt faint. Resolved after 5-10 minutes of sitting down, did not feel clear headed after that for several days. Did do her daily walk, starting on 2-28-2021, felt like she had less stamina.  Feels more tired in general still now. Does regret getting the COVID vaccine now. Took some benadryl at the time of the reaction and at hs PRN, benadryl makes her feel drowsy. Takes zyrtec, flonase daily and singulair. Pt's husband is a physician, and he prescribed a Medrol dose-pak, which did not seem to help. At the time was taking all of her prescribed medications amlodipine, benazepril. Has taken pepcid for heart burn in the past, was not taking it as the time.  Taking prn omeprazole. Denies experiencing any wheezing. Experienced Generalized swelling of eyelids, face, hands, feet. Tongue is kind of swollen today, and she feels like it has been swollen on and off since the vaccine. Prior to the vaccine she felt pretty good overall. Went out for a few days and went skiing with her family. Has a place out of town that she deep cleaned, felt like maybe she over did it, but she recovered after she rested briefly. Was due for the second vaccine last week. She held off until she could discuss with her doctor, and they discussed that she should not have any further doses. Physically she felt that she should not receive the 2nd vaccine. Continued  symptoms include itchy throat (tickle), vaginal and anal itching all day every day. Itching has become a little more like soreness of the tissues.  No bruising. Patient has not had the shingles vaccine (Shingrix), thinks she should not get it now. She has pretty much avoided getting vaccines throughout her life b/c she has had poor reactions to flu shots in the past as well.  One year, we tried a "half-dose" regimen of the flu shot, giving 0.5ml IM , waiting one month and repeating 0.5ml IM.  She did tolerate this well with no reported adverse outcome and did not get influenza that year though it was very active in the community. Since the Moderna vaccine, pt describes  Abd distention, bloating of small intestine, "I look 6 months pregnant." pt states her stomach has been like this since the COVID vaccine reaction.
OTHER_MEDS: Singulair 10mg, Amlodipine/Benazepril 5/10mg, estradiol 0.01% vaginal cream, Soothe XP 1%-4.5% eye drops, omeprazole 40mg, Zyrtec 10mg, Flonase 50mcg/spray nasal spray, tumeric root extract, vitamin D3

The itch continued to increase after leaving the site, and by 6 pm it had become like an ?morphine drip? type itch . An itch that you get after a procedure in a hospital and they give you opioids. An annoyance but harmless. This has continued for 3 days.  After the  first day, I asked a pharmacist what would be recommended for the itch. She suggested benedryl. After  the 3 day I went to the urgent care  where no testing was done, but I was prescribed hydroxyline

SYMPTOM_TEXT: By 4 PM  3/30/2021 , I had chills.  The next morning I had a congested headache that was really bad, chills, and a slight sore throat at times. And a temp of 100.9. A day later I also had a large red area on my arm....under the injection site.  It was smooth....and approximately  3 inches width and height. It itched slightly.  Today 4 days later, it is still red but a slightly smaller area.  I have not gone for any treatment.  I drank gatorade the first two days and took tylenol.  But I have not taken any of that yesterday or today.

Dose 1: Severe headache for the next day, minor pain and moderate stiffness of R arm over the next 24 hours.  I am *not* submitting this report for the first dose.  Dose 2: Moderate headache over next day, mild fatigue over next day, moderate joint pain over next day, same discomfort/stiffness of R arm.    The one thing I wanted to report was my L shoulder.   I had pulled/torn it around Wednesday of the week and it hurt quite a bit when I put it in the wrong position, but it was otherwise fine.   However, post-second Pfizer shot, the pain in my L shoulder easily double or tripped for some reason as a reaction to the vaccine.   Basically, Friday before the shot, my should hurt a little bit but had been getting progressively better.  But post-second Pfizer shot, the same area that had mild pain before now felt like I had been stabbed in the shoulder or that I had re-torn the muscle and had done so in a significantly worse way.     It's not a big thing, but you may want to start asking people if they've recently had any muscle injuries prior to vaccination.  I'm now ~30 hours post vaccine and it is decreasing in pain, but the shot obviously had some type of impact on what bruising/swelling/tearing of my L shoulder that I had.  (Note that both vaccine shots were to the R arm and the L should was not related to that in any way.)
OTHER_MEDS: Vitamin C 1,000 MG, Vitamin D3 50 MCG, Omeprazol 20 MG, probiotic.
ALLERGIES: Intolerance to Acetaminophen (not a full blow allergic reaction, but can cause nausea).

It was a small task that I simply could not comprehend.  I was not nauseous and was not dizzy.  I. finally ate something because I knew I should.  I felt totally wiped out. Approximately 48 hours after vaccination, I experienced sudden onset of tachycardia (heart rate ~130-150) which continued into the morning (April 1st 2021). The tachycardia transitioned into atrial flutter (confirmed by an EKG in the cardiologists office that afternoon)  with associated shortness of breath (secondary to the cardiac arrhythmia).  I had a cardio version that afternoon (4/1/2021, 4:00pm)  and converted to normal sinus rhythm. I was given a rhythm and rate modifier medication and anticoagulant.   Prior to the COVID vaccination,  I had been symptom free for 3 years from my atrial fibrillation and atrial flutter.
HISTORY: None. I had cardiac a-fib 3 years prior to the COVID vaccination which was successfully treated with an ablation.  I have been symptom free until 2 days after my COVID vaccination.

Patient presented today for her second COVID-19 vaccination. Before processing her dose, she expressed concerns over a reaction she had to her first dose.  After her first dose, she had nausea/vomiting and generalized hives and presented to the ER. Her treatment included IV benadryl followed by oral benadryl ATC until her hives subsided. She was hesitant to receive her second dose, but we encouraged her to go ahead and that we were prepared with benadryl if she needed it again and asked that she wait an extended 30 minutes post vaccination. Patient received her vaccine at 3:15pm and sat down. After about 10 minutes she started getting hot and nauseous.  She did vomit twice but said she was feeling better than she did after her first dose.  However, at 3:30 she started feeling itchy and could feel hives forming. I gave her 25mg of benadryl and we sat her by a fan.  at 3:48 she was still feeling a little itchy so I gave her another dose of 25mg of benadryl.  At 4:00 she insisted she was "feeling ok and wanted to go home because her daughter was there to pick her up and she was just so embarrassed about her reaction". EMT observed the client looking distressed and uncomfortable, so he approached her in the observation seating area around 1150. Patient expressed ?tightness in chest? and ?felt like she was going to black out, about 1 minute and 30 seconds into her 15 minute observation period.? EMT gave the client a water bottle and made sure it was safe to move the client, before transferring her into the zero- gravity chair.RN, PHN responded next. Client stated she has no known allergies, has no medical conditions to be aware of, and has no previous reactions to any other vaccines. First set of vitals were taken at 1153 while client was sitting; client was alert and oriented, Blood Pressure (BP): 112/88, Heart Rate (HR): 108, Respiratory Rate (RR): 28, skin was warm, dry, tact and normal for ethnicity, capillary refill was within normal limits. Nurse observed the client?s hands to be shaking. Client was then advised to stay an additional 30 minutes by the EMTs for further observation- client agreed. Client reported the feeling of tightness in her chest resolved around 1156. She also expressed that ?she had never had a panic attack before and that the medical environment made her feel uneasy because she does not like needles.? Second set of vitals were taken at 1158 while client was sitting; client was alert and oriented, Blood Pressure (BP): 100/65, Heart Rate (HR): 64, Respiratory Rate (RR): 20, skin was warm, dry, tact and normal for ethnicity, capillary refill was within normal limits. Nurse observed the shaking in the client?s hands had resolved. Last set of vitals were taken 1223 while client was sitting; client was alert and oriented, Blood Pressure (BP): 110/70, Heart Rate (HR): 60, Respiratory Rate (RR): 17, skin was warm, dry, tact and normal for ethnicity, capillary refill was within normal limits. After this set of vitals, the client stated she ?was feeling way better.? Nurse educated client on the importance of eating and hydrating before she receives her second dose and that if she had additional symptoms or questions to call her provider. Client walked out the vaccine site with a steady gait.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Sat. 3-13-2021 at 11:53am, Janssen covid shot was administered in left arm.  Approximately 3 hours later, at about 3:10pm, I started seeing bright flashing arcs of light in my upper left vision.  I wondered if these were precursors of a migraine coming, but mine normally are crackles of primary colors in the center of my vision.  I remembered the vitreous detachment in my right eye 5 years ago.  This seemed similar, but not very similar.  Around 6pm I noticed a largish donut in my left eye vision, which I've never seen before.  About 7:30pm I called the consulting nurse, who told me to go to Urgent Care.  Got there about 8pm.  The MD thought it was a vitreous detachment, but wanted to get an OD on the phone. Additional floaters appeared in my left eye vision while I waited.  OD via phone thought it was a vitreous detachment and set up an appointment to see me on Mon. 3-15-2021.  Flashing arcs/donut/floaters continued through the next day.  Last flashing arcs were about noon on Mon. 3-15-2021.  In total the flashing arcs lasted about 45 hours.  5 years ago, in the right eye, flashing lights lasted only 5-10 minutes. On Mon. 3-15-2021 had eye exam. OD said posterior vitreous detachment (PVD).  Wanted second opinion about my retina.  Second OD performed exam, agreed on PVD and that my retina looked okay. On Fri. 4-2-2021 had follow-up exam with same OD.  Retina looked good.  Floaters are diminishing. What terrible timing if this was a coincidence.  It made everything post-covid-shot very confusing.
LAB_DATA: 3-15-2021:  2 eye exams (2 different eye doctors). 4-2-2021:    Follow-up eye exam.
OTHER_MEDS: Multi-vitamin, calcium/magnesium/zinc, B-complex, vitamin C, docusate sodium, NasalCrom nasal spray for spring/summer pollen allergies, aspirin or Exedrin Migraine when needed for migraines.
HISTORY: Pollen allergies, migraines from synthetic fragrances, cigarette smoke, auto exhaust
ALLERGIES: Thimerosal, Nizoral/Ketoconazole, Amoxicillin, chlorine, Systane Balance eye drops.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Day 1: Monday 15 minutes of routine waiting at the pharmacy for any immediate reaction. Nothing immediately. Went about my day. Sore arm developed later in the afternoon. No biggie.   Day 2: Tuesday. 24 hours later. Reeeeallllly sore arm, feeling okay. An hour after waking up: BAM. Immediately felt lightheaded, dizzy, thought I was going to pass out. Nausea. Pounding headache. No ability to do work the entire day. The couch was my friend. Moving my arm throughout the day alleviated arm soreness. Felt slightly better in the early evening. This was my worst day.  Day 3: Wednesday: 48 hours later. Headache. Energy in the morning. Wave hit me around noon and I was down the rest of the afternoon. Pounding headache. Lightheaded. Nausea. Waves of this mix throughout the day.  Day 4: Thursday: 72 hours later. Thought I had improved but headache quickly set in within an hour or two of waking up. Zoom meeting the first half of the day, tiredness set in halfway through, then waves of feeling lightheaded with headache and occasional nausea throughout the day.   Day 5: Friday: 96 hours later: Headache and waves of struggle all day.   Day 6: Saturday: 120+ hours later (at this time of writing!). Slight lingering headache. Best day so far. Was overcome by stronger headache and tiredness in the afternoon (starting around 3:00pm)

Patient presented to the pharmacy on 4/2/21 to ask about side effects she was experiencing from her 2nd dose of Moderna COVID-19 vaccine. She stated that she received her second dose on 3/29/21, and at this time was still having side effects. When asked what side effects she was experiencing, she showed me her arm which had a large red area (approximately the size of a baseball) that appeared to wrap around her arm. She said this area was painful, itchy, and warm as well. She said she experience this since the day of getting her second dose, but her symptoms had improved slightly since. I recommended she follow up with her primary care provider as soon as possible, which she said she had an appointment for the following day. She asked if she could do anything regarding the pain, redness, and itchiness and I told her it would be okay in the meantime (until her follow up with her primary care provider) to use over the counter pain relievers for some pain relief, and diphenhydramine topical cream for relief of the itching and redness.   I tried to follow up with the patient today to check in and see if there had been any improvement since yesterday (especially since new information came to light - see below), but she was unavailable for contact. Prior to submitting this report, I took a look at the patient medication profile at our pharmacy and discovered her COVID-19 first dose was on 3/22/21, and she received her second dose on 3/29/21 (21 days earlier than she should have received it). At this time my district pharmacy manager and patient care services manager have been made aware of this incident, and am awaiting guidance from them once they make contact with Moderna regarding the early administered dose.
CUR_ILL: HYPERTENSION, HYPERCHOLESTEROLEMIA, CONGESTIVE HEART FAILURE, ATRIAL FIBRILLATION
HISTORY: HYPERTENSION, HYPERCHOLESTEROLEMIA, CONGESTIVE HEART FAILURE, ATRIAL FIBRILLATION

Patient woke up around 3:30am feeling extremely nauseous, shaking, drenched in sweat but with a normal temperature (97.6, which is normal for him), and feeling overall terrible.  Food had tasted weird to him the day before, but he still ate. At 3:30am, he felt like he was having a major allergy attack - lots of phlegm, runny nose and eyes. He spit up a lot of thick phlegm (which can be normal for him, due to IBM). After 15 mins, the sweat and shaking died down, and he felt better enough to think about going to sleep. But 5 minutes later, the nausea returned, and he threw up about 25 mL of black "coffee grounds-like" fluid. (The smell was HORRIBLE). After getting through with that (about 15 minutes), he wretched up more thick mucus with a few flecks of black cells in it. After awhile, he felt okay enough to go back to sleep.  Around 6am, he had another major allergy-like attack, but did not vomit.  Around 8am, after being awake for awhile, he vomited again with more black liquid, about 50mL this time. He felt weak and horrible and was shaking. At the recommendation of the advice nurse, he was taken to the ER by ambulance. Upon arriving, he waited around an hour for an ER bed.  They put him on an IV, did a physical inspection and did blood work. His sodium was a bit low, but in normal range. Potassium levels were fine. He was mentally clear the whole time, but physically very weak.  He was kept overnight after a hemochrit test in the afternoon showed low levels of hemoglobin. He was stabilized in the morning, but was barely able to eat anything the whole time. He was meant to get an endoscopy, but they decided to allow him to eat and sent him home after noon bc they hadn't yet been able to schedule him for it and he was in pain and massively hungry.  When he got home, he still barely ate,  and still isn't eating almost anything a day later. His stool was incredibly black and thick and SMELLY immediately upon arriving home (he had not defecated for 48 hours at that point), and he has not been able to defecate since, which is extremely abnormal (he usually goes each day in the morning upon waking).  They believe that he may have bleeding in his stomach or upper GI or esophagus, but we are waiting for an endoscopy later this week.  He is still very weak and frail and fatigued.

On Saturday, April 3, 2021 clientt received her first dose of Pfizer COVID vaccine (LOT # EW0150, EXP 7/2021) at approximately 2:00pm. After vaccine was administered, client was to wait in the Observaton Area for 30 minutes due to Penicillin and sulfa drug allergy. At 2:09pm, client walked up to EMT and stated she was "feeling light-headed." Client was advised to sit in the anti-gravity chair and was given a bottle of water. Upon assessment by EMTs, client's last meal was at 12:30pm. Client also stated to EMTs she felt light-headed right after receiving the vaccine. At 2:13pm, the client stated the back of her neck felt "a little tight" and stated she had a headache. At 2:15pm vitals were taken: BP: 130/76, Hr: 57, RR: 15, O2 sat: 97%. Lead PHN was notified and advised client to be watched for an additional 30 minutes. Vitals at 2:20pm: BP: 128/78, HR: 59, O2 sat: 98%. Vitals at 2:25pm: BP: 128/70, HR: 59, O2 sat: 97%. At approximately 2:40pm, client stated her light-headedness and tightness on the back of her neck completely subsided. Patient was alert and oriented x4 during entire interaction. No further interventions indicated. Client was educated by Lead RN & EMT on signs and symptoms of adverse reactions and when to go to the ED/call MD. Client was also encouraged to sign-up on v-safe. Client was able to ambulate with EMTs to her car with a steady gait at approximately 3pm.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within the first hour, developed headache and neck ache  (back of neck where neck meets head) and arm ache all on right side of body, same side as injection. Also developed a slightly chemical taste in my mouth, which lasted 36 hours. Within 5 hours, headache, neck ache, arm ache significantly painful; applied gel ice packs to head and right arm; went to bed early. Awoke at midnight with entire right arm, down to hand, feeling like it was in a steel-toothed trap; pain was excruciating, and while I was able to rotate arm and flex hand, pain level was very high. At same time, neck ache was very high, felt like a boulder was sitting on it. At same time, had blistering migraine with runny nose and eye. Called family doctor's office at 8am next day to ask whether I could take migraine medication (elatriptan or sumatriptan) after vaccine; office closed but nurse in call center told me to go to ER; I suggested the side effects were very painful but listed as possible, and didn't knwo that they warranted ER, and just wanted to know whether I could take triptan for agonizing migraine; nurse didn't really know how to respond. I went back to bed with ice. A few hours later, a family member called their doctor's office and was told yes, I could safely take triptan. Took sumatriptan at 1pm and it cut the migraine way back, to a manageable level. Over the course of the first 24 hours after vaccine, also felt lightheaded, woozy, nauseous, hot, cold sweats, digestive upset and loose stool, diminished appetite. Checked temperature a few times, but it was normal. At 5pm of second day, took 2 Tylenol, which helped pain. Waited 24 hours before taking 2 more Tylenol. By end of second full day after vaccine, feeling better, but like I had a bad head cold with mild headache.

On an unknown date, the outcome of the vaccination failure and chronic hepatitis b were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the vaccination failure and chronic hepatitis b to be related to Hepatitis B vaccine.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the suspected vaccination failure, in a patient more than or equal to 19-year-old of unspecified gender, who was vaccinated with Unspecified Hepatitis B vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis.   The patient was a part of a retrospective study whose primary objective was to examine the number of patients with acute hepatitis B virus (HBV) infection managed at a campus from 1st January 2015 to 31st December 2018, as well as their characteristics and serological and clinical outcomes. A secondary objective was to evaluate the diagnosis and treatment at the institution, based on national standards. No information on patient medical or family history or concurrent condition or concomitant medication was reported.  On an unknown date, the patient received unspecified Hepatitis B vaccination (administration site unspecified, dose number unknown; batch number not provided) upon diagnosis of HIV. The age at vaccination was not provided. [In this study, out of the 5 patients born after 1991, when the recommendation for universal HBV child vaccination was issued, only 1 confirmed having been vaccinated]. On an unspecified date 1st January 2015 to 31st December 2018, an unknown period after vaccination, the patient was noted with positive hepatitis B surface antigen (HBsAg). The patient had either jaundice or elevated alanine aminotransferase (ALT) levels more than 100 IU/L without alternative explanation; either an acute illness with a discrete onset of any sign or symptom consistent with acute viral hepatitis (eg, fever, headache, malaise, anorexia, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, and abdominal pain) without alternative explanation or a documented negative HBsAg within the prior 6 months or a positive hepatitis B core (HBc) IgM antibody. The patient was diagnosed with acute Hepatitis B infection initially and later developed chronic HBV infection. [In this study, defined a case of acute hepatitis B with the following criteria: (1) a positive hepatitis B surface antigen (HBsAg) and (2) either jaundice or elevated alanine aminotransferase (ALT) levels more than 100 IU/L without alternative explanation and (3) either (a) an acute illness with a discrete onset of any sign or symptom consistent with acute viral hepatitis (eg, fever, headache, malaise, anorexia, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, and abdominal pain) without alternative explanation or (b) a documented negative HBsAg within the prior 6 months or (c) a positive hepatitis B core (HBc) IgM antibody. Outcome measures included clinical course, use of anti-HBV treatment, and progression to chronic infection, using the American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases (AASLD) criteria. A protracted-severe course was defined as either more than 4 weeks of an elevated INR (more than or equal to 1.5) or total bilirubin more than 3 mg/dL (or direct more than 1.5 mg/dL) or clinical evidence of encephalopathy or ascites. The lack of these criteria defined an uncomplicated course. Following AASLD guidelines, indications for anti-HBV treatment included protracted severe course, and acute liver failure was defined as an elevated INR (more than or equal to 1.5) with evidence of altered sensorium in a patient without preexisting cirrhosis. HBsAg positivity for at least 6 months after the initial HBsAg positive result defined chronic HBV infection. 36 cases of acute HBV were identified during the study period, 8 in 2015-2016 and 28 in 2017-2018. A history of intravenous drug use (IVDU) was identified in 8 patients, and all of these had acute hepatitis B in 2017 and 2018. Two patients reported vaccination against HBV several years before the infection. One of them was vaccinated upon diagnosis of HIV infection. More than half of patients did not follow up after diagnosis of acute HBV, and therefore their clearance status could not be determined. Seventeen patients had follow-up HBsAg testing, and 1 developed chronic HBV infection. This patient was co-infected with HIV, and his antiretroviral regimen included lamivudine as the only drug active against HBV. One patient with Crohn's disease, who was on treatment with mesalamine at the time of the infection, cleared the HBsAg by the 14th month after acute illness]. The case was considered as suspected vaccination failure being dosing schedule and time to onset unknown. The case was considered as serious due to suspected vaccination failure. Treatment was unknown. Outcome was not reported. The authors commented "Our data suggest that IVDU has contributed to an increase in acute hepatitis B cases in our community at least since 2017. This coincides with a national uptrend in drug abuse, an epidemic ongoing for more than a decade. In the HBV vaccination efforts, new ways of identifying individuals at high risk and additional venues to deliver the vaccine could be considered. On this regard, in our study one-third of the patients had used the hospital emergency room within the prior year, and more than half had psychiatric disease. Limited vaccine effectiveness constitutes another barrier in the fight against HBV. Thus, 2 of our patients became infected despite prior vaccination, 1 of whom was HIV-positive. As HIV infection is not only a well-recognized risk factor for poorer response to the HBV vaccine but also for developing chronic infection, including tenofovir as part of the HIV treatment can confer additional protection. The patient who developed chronic HBV was infected with HIV, an association that is well recognized, with an estimated risk up to 6 times higher than non-HIV hosts. Interestingly, we observed spontaneous HBsAg clearance after 6 months in 1 patient with Crohn's disease. Itis unclear if this delay was related to Crohn's in the absence of immunosuppressive therapy.".   The authors concluded "In summary, our study confirms that the IVDU epidemic is implicated in the surge of HBV cases in our community, and it highlights the importance of additional efforts for vaccination targeting at-risk individuals at all possible levels of care. We identified opportunities to inform and prepare our health care providers while the opioid epidemic continues in order to better align the diagnosis and management of acute HBV with national guidelines". This article is not available for regulatory submission due to copyright restriction.

This 76-year-old female consumer (patient herself) reported that she received first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, Formulation: Solution for injection, Lot number: EL3246) via an unspecified route in Left arm on 16Jan2021 being 02:34 PM (at the age of 76-years-old) as single dose for COVID-19 immunisation. Concomitant medications were not reported. Patient stated that her husband and her took the first dose of the vaccine on Saturday 16Jan2021. She says she was fine Saturday, then she woke up on Sunday morning with a headache behind her eyes that was not bad but she noticed it most of the day and then at night it was behind her eyes, the top of her head, and behind her head on 17Mar2021 at 07:00. She says she has had headaches all last week, and she took Advil and Tylenol which sometimes helped. She says she finally saw her doctor last Friday on the 22nd because she felt that was a long time for her to have headaches as a result of a vaccine and her doctor had her do a CAT scan to be sure, since she is 76, to check if she might be having a stroke or something. She says she has continued to have headaches, though not as bad as last week, and she was reading the material they got at the hospital because they are supposed to have the second shot 06Feb2021. She says she would like to know, have they had people report having headaches that long. She says she took both Tylenol, clarified to being Equate brand Acetaminophen, and Advil. Equate brand Acetaminophen: She says she has two bottles one of which she keeps in the bedroom, so she doesn't know which bottle her doses came from. She says both of the Equate brand Acetaminophen bottles are extra strength, 500mg. She says when she took these two medications she was careful not to overtake or take too much, but she can't really tell how much she took. She says she thinks she first took one Tylenol and one Advil, then later that night when it really bothered her, she thinks she took maybe two Advil's and one Tylenol, but she didn't write it down. She says now her headache is not nearly like it was last week. She says that she spoke to her doctor on Friday because she was starting to get concerned about it, but it was not unbearable all day long, she would wake up with it then take something, and during the day it was better, then at night it would be worse. She says this week it mainly bothered her that it was at the back of her head and neck area, since she does have problems sometimes with headaches at the back of her head after she had a car accident in 2009 where she got hit from behind that caused issues with her neck. She says she doesn't have sinus issues, so the headache behind her eyes was odd, and since the information said side effect, it is too big of a coincidence that she got the shot Saturday and she had a headache on Sunday. probably in 2009, and she started taking Amlodipine 5mg then, and then after she retired from teaching her doctor decided she didn't need it and she stopped taking it. Investigation results were also received on 10Mar2021 for PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE INJECTABLE Lack Of Effect. Summary of Investigation: The initial scope of the investigation was limited to the reported finished goods lot. The final scope was expanded to include the reported finished goods lot EL9264, fill lot EL9255, and the formulated drug product lot EL9246. Manufacturing and packaging batch records were reviewed for the reported complaint lot. (Site Name) QO did not receive photographs or a complaint sample for examination. The complaint was not confirmed. There were no planned or unplanned deviations recorded during the manufacture of the complaint lot and associated manufacturing lots that may have caused a complaint of this nature. A review of the manufacturing records confirmed processing steps were performed within pre-established parameters. During formulation of PBS Buffer, there was an undercharge of disodium hydrogen phosphate dihydrate, but this was found to have no impact on product quality. All other raw materials used in the complaint batch were of the correct weight and identity. The drug product is stored at controlled refrigeration throughout the manufacturing process and a log is maintained documenting the elapsed time out of refrigeration. A review of the logs confirmed that all times were within allowable limits. The product also requires storage in ultra-low temperature freezers following the packaging of the product. A review of the freezer temperature log for the reported batch confirmed that all freezer temperatures were within allowable limits. The results of all analytical tests performed at the time of lot release confirmed that the batch meets potency specifications. Not process/vendor related. Final Confirmation Status: Not Confirmed. Batch record review included the reported finished goods lot EL9264, fill lot EL9255, and the bulk formulated drug product EL9246. Acceptable review of related documentation, including manufacturing and packaging batch records and review of release test results at the time of lot release confirmed that there were no issues which may have resulted in a complaint of this nature. Visual examination of a reserve sample would not be expected to indicate the potency of the drug product. A reserve sample was not sent to the QC-lab to determine the amount of active ingredient since the complaint was received within six months of the release date of the involved batch. The results of all analytical tests performed at the time of lot release were confirmed to be within registered specifications. All available stability results for this product were within registered specification and stability studies (including accelerated studies) are ongoing for this product. No lot trend or other trend identified. As of 10Mar2021, a total of three complaints have been received for this lot and classification. No lot specific trend was identified that would require additional investigation. Conclusion: The complaint for lack of effect of the PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE lot EL9264 was investigated. The investigation included a review of manufacturing and packaging batch records, deviation investigations, and an analysis of complaint history for the reported lot and product type. The final scope included the reported finished goods lot EL9264, fill lot EL9255, and the formulated drug product lot EL9246. A complaint sample was not returned. No related quality issues were identified during the investigation. There is no impact on product quality. No root cause or CAPA were identified as the complaint was not confirmed. All release testing performed prior to the release of the reported batch was within specifications.

On 12Mar2021, 13:15 the patient eyes began to water and itch, slightly blurred vision, discharge in both eyes, sensitive to light, substantial fatigue. The patient had 2 major side effects. Both occurred about 2 hours after getting the vaccination. Both worsened as the day went on. The patient had involuntary squint because of itchy and watering eyes, dried discharge closing eyes in morning upon rising. They got significantly worse the following day. His eyes began to water and itch, and vision got slightly blurry. He attributed that to his eyes watering constantly. He does not wear glasses and has close to 20/20 even though he was old. He looks at computer and reads a lot. It got worse until Monday, then it abated slightly. It was still substantial. The right eye was worse than left. Two hours after watery and itching, he did not notice any blurry vision. That was later in the afternoon. As he was writing documents on computer and reading printed material was when he noticed it. There was enough discharge from the watering and tearing that when you wake up, you feel your eyes are glued closed. It has improved slightly in one eye. But it was the same or worse in right eye. Sensitivity to light began around 2 hours after the vaccination while he was in the car driving. Substantial fatigue got worse that night and was moderately bad Saturday, Sunday and Monday. It had abated moderately yesterday and then was worse yesterday and today, but better than the weekend. IT comes and goes and is not continuous. He has never had malaria but thinks it was the same feeling of overwhelming fatigue. He does not have any previous pre-existing conditions. It began with the vaccination. He was not a person of hypochondria and was not particularly worried about this. He was not worried about dying. They are simple side effects with any vaccine. The patient was disturbed when he looked it up. He did not see any symptoms being advertised about eye problems and he was very educated about it. Then when he looked it up, he saw others that had the same thing if not worse. He does not have any information for people that experienced the same thing that he read about online on the internet. Many symptoms that people were reporting were much more severe such as: eyes puffy, face swelling and eyes itchy and crusty. He must have seen 30-35 on two websites that reported and many more on websites on the internet. He then said it could have been 35-40 that he read carefully. Everyone in his family had the vaccine. His son had first dose and experienced no real symptoms. His wife who is a nurse had it 3 weeks ago and only a mild twinge in her arm. She experienced some fatigue yesterday for second dose. It was not really important and nothing that has not been reported. He did not wish to complete report. He was the healthiest person in the family, and he was surprised that he got these side effects. After he got the eye issues, he took Visine. Visine Advanced only clears were up for 10 minutes and then it comes right back. He only used it a few times because it was useless. If the vaccine had not blinded him, he could see the lot number easier. Lot is JJB0300 with expiration Sep2021. It was a total size of 0.284 ounces or 8ml. Visine Advanced gets rid of bloodshot eyes like for drunks. He does not drink though. He would not be willing to send a sample and it was sealed and intact. The patient uses the cetirizine (tablet, 10mg, Lot: 0EE27118 and Expiration date: Jan2022) oral from 13Mar2021 at 10mg twice a day taken for eye problems related to vaccine. hemoglobin 8.7 g/dL and platelets 60*109/L; bloody diarrhea; This is a literature-spontaneous report based on the journal following Pfizer and Moderna SARS-CoV-2 vaccination. The same author reported different events for 4 patients received Pfizer vaccine. This is the 1st of 4 reports.  The reports describing 19 of 20 patients with thrombocytopenia following vaccination Pfizer and Moderna SARS-CoV-2 vaccination, included age (range 22-73 years old; median 41 years) and gender (11 females and 8 males). Nine received the Pfizer vaccine and 11 received the Moderna vaccine. All 20 patients were hospitalized and most patients presented with petechiae, bruising or mucosal bleeding (gingival, vaginal, epistaxis) with onset of symptoms between 1-23 days (median 5 days) post vaccination. Platelet counts at presentation were available for all 20 cases with the majority being at or below 10*109/L (range 1-36*109/L; median 2*109/L).  This case refers to an 80-year-old male patient with multiple medical problems including recent transcatheter aortic valve replacement, hypothyroidism, and diverticulosis presented 6 days after the Pfizer vaccine with bloody diarrhea, hemoglobin 8.7 g/dL and platelets 60*109/L. He received several units of packed red blood cells and two units of platelets with improvement to 101*109/L and was discharged 5 days later. There were a handful of reports with minimal additional details alluding to a male who passed away in Dec2020 from brain hemorrhage following the Pfizer vaccine-these could be describing the index patient. There were a handful of reports with minimal additional details alluding to a male who passed away in December from brain hemorrhage following the Pfizer vaccine-these could be describing the index patient.  In summary, we cannot exclude the possibility that the Pfizer and Moderna vaccines have the potential to trigger de novo ITP (including clinically undiagnosed cases), albeit very rarely. Distinguishing vaccine-induced ITP from coincidental ITP presenting soon after vaccination is impossible at this time.  No follow up attempts are needed; information about lot/batch number cannot be obtained. No further information is expected.; Sender's Comments: Based on the information currently provided (plausible time association), it cannot be fully excluded that the SARS-CoV-2 vaccination might have played a contributory role in triggering the occurrence of thrombocytopenia complicated by bloody diarrhea leading to blood loss requiring blood products infusion.  The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. SYMPTOM_TEXT: DOSE #1      After about an hour, my face was flushed and arm sore, of course.      Later 1st day and for next 5 days, EXTREMELY fatigued and tired; VERY hard to concentrate. Sinuses felt a bit congested during this time. Also had difficulty staying asleep first 3 nights after injection. Tiredness and fatigue took approx. 2 1/2 weeks to resolve completely.      After 2nd day I began to experience joint pain and swelling, including elbow and knee. I do not normally have any problems with this. I could barely bend my knee. These symptoms lasted over a week. During this time I also had episodes of mild dizziness and nausea, but nothing that hindered my daily activities.        Redness at injection site, which at one point was 4 - 5 inches in diameter, lasted approx. 2 1/2 weeks before it completely disappeared.  DOSE #2 (03/30/2021)       No problem sleeping after 2nd dose.      Much more pain/redness at injection site.      Again, experiencing extreme fatigue, feeling exhausted, difficulty concentrating.  This time joint pain/swelling is minor.      With the 2nd dose, I also am experiencing swollen lymph nodes (left side, underarm), and a odd taste in my mouth 24/7.      I expect this too will resolve after a few weeks.   In addition to the allergies listed on page one, I do have many other allergies and sensitivities (too many to list on this form). I cannot have wine due to sulfites, processed meat due to nitrites and nitrates, I stay away from most processed food, am allergic to cats and dogs, and have severe reactions to wasp/bee/bug stings and/or bites.  Last year I was stung by a wasp on my ear and hand. The complications of extreme swelling, pain, dizziness, nausea, swollen lymph nodes in my neck/throat area, took more than a month to resolve.  I can not eat or drink anything with artificial sweetener. The list goes on...  So, I am not surprised I reacted like I did to the vaccine. However, I was grateful to have this vaccine and feel fortunate to have had the opportunity.          Thank you and have a wonderful day!
OTHER_MEDS: IRBESARTAN, PANTOPRAZOLE, ZONISAMIDE, DAILY VITAMIN, CALCIUM

She presented  to the ER on 2/13 with a lot of chest pain and had some flattening of her T waves.  She ended up getting a cardiac catheterization while she was there which was normal.   The day prior to this she had actually received her second Covid vaccination in her left arm.  She noticed achiness and soreness across her shoulders bilaterally into her chest and into her neck.  She had some subjective fevers and chills and felt generally fatigued.  She also had a lot of swelling in her left axilla and she ended up getting a CT scan during her workup which revealed some left axillary adenopathy.  She returned to the ER on 3/16: while brushing her teeth, she developed right facial paresthesias that marched over approximately 20 minutes to involve the right arm and the right leg.  She went to the hospital.  She was seen in the ER.  They felt this represented possible ischemia.  They gave her tPA.  She had a hemorrhagic nosebleed.  Did not develop any other signs of bleeding. Her symptoms had not resolved.  She was discharged from home.  She had a headache at the time of her visit to the ER.  Her headache had resolved by the time she was discharged home, but she continues to note paresthesias in the right side of her body, right face, and notes over the last day or 2, she has had increased dysarthria, dizziness and slurred speech, brain fog, a sensation of heaviness and inability to think.  She states she currently does not have head pain per se, but she does note that she just feels generally poorly.  She feels like her brain is working faster than her mouth muscles are.  She is in today for neurologic followup, concerned about these ongoing issues.  she continues to struggle with her speech feeling quite slow and deliberate, she feels like it is difficult for her to concentrate, she is forgetful, she still has intermittent episodes of paresthesias in her face, arm, and hand, she feels like she becomes heart and flushed and she has some heart rate variability with her heart going slow and fast, and she has significant disequilibrium.  She is extremely fatigued where she is only able to get up for 1-2 hours before she is extremely fatigued and has to go back to bed.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Joint pain, fever/chills, headache

Five days after my second vaccine, at about 8 am, I developed fairly diffuse abdominal pain, and retching.  I left work and went home.  This lasted for about 3 to 4 hours, then let up, but then developed about 45 minutes of profound rigors, which then let up, then my temperature (had been normal) went up to less than 102 F.  For the next six days I continued to run fever, never higher than 103, chills, and some migrating abdominal pain, no diarrhea, normal stools, constipated if anything.  Stayed home from work obviously.  On Sunday, and Monday am, still running fevers, my pain seemed to settle into my right lower quadrant.      My wife, a family physician, helped arrange a CT scan Abdomen and Pelvis, as we were concerned about appendicitis, maybe an abscess.  The scan revealed normal appendix, but several lesions in the right side of the liver thought highly suspicious for "metastatic disease."  MRI recommended, and had this Wednesday that week, and it confirmed the lesions, with characteristics suspicious for metastatic tumors.  By Monday afternoon, my fever abated, and I felt much better.  Able to return to work.  The abdominal discomfort was improved, maybe due to constipation.  Friday of that week, I was able to get to see my primary provider, who is in Omaha, NE to review the situation, and we agreed a liver biopsy was needed.       A week later, Friday, Jan. 29, I had CT guided liver biopsy at  hospital in Omaha. 16 cores taken, and no malignancy found, but significant inflammatory cells, especially lymphocytes.  Meanwhile I have felt fine.  Decided to do a follow up MRI of liver, which was done Friday, April 2, and all the areas have resolved.    There is an entity called "Inflammatory pseudotumors" of the liver, and my condition fits with this.  It is very rare.     A consideration would be whether it would be possible to stain the biopsy to see if the lymphocytes carry antibodies to the corona virus.
LAB_DATA: normal cbc, cmp, elevated sed rate, MRI  and CT as described.
OTHER_MEDS: lipitor; pepcid; vit B12; folic acid; vit C: vit D

SYMPTOM_TEXT: JANSSEN COVID-19 VACCINE EUA  I received the vaccine on 3rd April, 2021, at approximately 9:30 am. There were no immediate side effects. I also experienced a fever and body soreness. My wife tended to me with two ibuprofen tablets, 200 mg each and continually to put cold presses on my forehead. I drank a lot of water but my fever continued to spike to 102.8. The symptoms continued for another 3 hours. Out of concern we called the emergency room to ask if we should be concerned about the fever. We were advised to take two Tylenol tablets. My wife gave me two Tylenol PM tablets. About 30 mins after taking the Tylenol tablets and continuing to hydrate, my cold and chills began to subside and I began to shed all of my layers. About 30 minutes after that, my fever levelled out to abougt 100.8. Then I passed out. The following morning, I woke up with cold, chills and fever gone. I had a mild headache and took 2 Extra Strength Tylenol tablets. It's been four hours since then and I feel fine, just a little weak.

Patient related that she has an alcohol sensitivity where she develops red and itchy skin following consumption of alcoholic beverages.  She relates she also experiences cold urticaria where she develops a red, itchy rash following submersion in cold water.  When this occurs, she typically takes Benadryl or Zyrtec/Claritin (depending on the time of day), of which resolves the itching and the rash subsides.  She has an allergy to Bactrim.  She relates a past medical history of asthma, which she takes a daily inhaler, as well as uses her rescue inhaler twice a week.  She has not seen her PCP in about 1 year.  She denies chest pain/tightness, shortness of breath, difficulty breathing, swelling of the face/lips/tongue/throat, skin rash/itching, cramping abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting.       Exam (update as needed): GEN: Alert and oriented x 4, in NAD HEAD: NCAT EYES: PERRL, EOMI ENT: Ears normal, Nose normal, OP normal, no evidence of angioedema NECK: Supple, without LAD.  CV: RRR, no m/r/g PULM: Clear to auscultation bilaterally, no accessory muscle use ABD: Soft, no tenderness. SKIN: Erythematous, coalescing raised papules in the distribution of the left forearm and left dorsal hand.  Small, erythematous wheal on the dorsum of the left shoulder.  No erythema or edema of the injection site.  Skin warm and dry MSK: FROM, MS 5/5 NEURO: Alert and oriented x 4, CN 2-12 grossly intact, no ataxia, gait steady   Clinical Impression/Field Tx: Urticarial rash.  Patient was observed for 15 minutes following 30 minute observation period.  During that time, the skin manifestations stabilized.  Patient did not display signs/symptoms of anaphylaxis.  Vital signs were stable.  Patient offered evaluation by EMS, however, patient denied evaluation and preferred to go home.  Patient was driven to site by significant other and self-administered OTC Benadryl.   Patient asked to follow up with PCP/allergist and to inform them of the post-vaccination reaction, as well as to further discuss asthma/urticaria management.  Patient instructed to go to the emergency department should she develop chest pain, shortness of breath, and swelling of the face/lips/mouth/tongue/throat, as these could be possible signs of anaphylaxis that require immediate attention.    Medications administered: None.  Patient self-administered OTC benadryl   Disposition:  Home

The headache subsided after approximately 20 minutes; the flushing went away within a couple of hours of receiving the vaccine.   Several hours after receiving the vaccine, I developed some minor itching. My arm continued to hurt more at the injection site (I never developed any redness or bruising at the site.) I experienced body aches and general malaise (as I was informed was to be expected.)  I continued to have the strong metallic taste in my mouth into the evening and nighttime hours following the vaccine. During the night (approximately 9 hours after receiving the vaccine,) I awoke to an unfamiliar odor, and feeling nauseous.  The odor was emitted from my skin.   It has been approximately  72 hours since I received the Pfizer COVID  vaccine. The skin odor and metallic state have lessened, but are still persistent.

The patient is a 45 y/o male prisoner who presented 4/3/2021 with 3 days of headache, neck pain and stiffness, sensitivity to light, and nausea.  He was found to have extensive dural venous sinus thrombosis causing the symptoms.  He has hypothyroidism was taking levothyroxine 150 mcg daily at time of vaccination.  On admission on 4/3/2021 his TSH was found to be 12 and levothyroxine dose was increased to 175 mcg on 4/4/2021.  He has no prior history of thrombosis and the only family member with thrombosis is his mother who had DVTs associated with lung cancer.  He has a history of prior COVID-19 infection in April of 2020 and at that time reported 3-4 days of mild symptoms and was not hospitalized or given anticoagulation.  He has not had fevers, chills, or other symptoms of infection.  He received his first dose of the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine at the prison on 3/23/2021 which was 9 days prior to symptom on set 12 days prior to presentation at the hospital.  He reports 2-3 days of arm soreness at the injection site in his right arm, mild neck soreness, and fatigue after the injection which had resolved prior to his current symptoms starting.  He currently remains hospitalized and is being treated with anticoagulation.
LAB_DATA: 4/3/2021 - CT Head - Extensive abnormally increased density of the intracranial venous structures, these findings are concerning for extensive cerebral venous thrombosis. Contrast-enhanced MRI brain and MRV are recommended for further evaluation. 4/4/2021 - MRI Brain -  There is extensive thrombosis involving the dural venous sinuses and the deep cerebral veins. No acute intracranial infarct or intracranial hemorrhage. 4/4/2021 - MRI Venogram - Extensive diffuse venous sinus thrombosis involving the dural sinuses and the deep cerebral veins 4/4/2021 - CT Neck with contrast -  Diffuse dural venous sinus thrombosis, with thrombus propagating out of the left jugular bulb into the cervical course of the left internal jugular vein for 3.8 cm

At the vaccination center they monitored my vitals and made me lie down for 30-40 mins after which i felt much better. Then I took the train home.  After getting to my apartment I lay down for a while and when i tried to get up i was very disoriented. I felt extremely dizzy, numbness and tingling was in my whole arms and legs and even my back. it felt like my skin was burning from the inside. Around 4 i began calling the university health center and covid hotlines because i wasn't feeling well at all. During this time i also experienced twitching of my face, hands and feet and a period of confusion - i wasn't able to keep the conversation with my nurse and tell her what my symptoms were. I also had trouble verbalizing. I was told to take Tylenol and ibuprofen. i took them but the fever came back.  Severe Stomach pain and nausea  I had fever till 4/2 - the highest temperature was 102.4 late in the night on 4/1.  on 4/2 i ended up having to call the healthcare again, they thought i should go to the ER, Then i went to urgent who sent me to ER. SYMPTOM_TEXT: After taking my 2nd Shot for Booster on the morning of Friday the 5th of 2021. I ate and hydrated for the day. At home I was resting when standing up I was overwhelmed with dizziness, nausea, sweats, and then the chills and heat hit. My inner core felt frozen. I couldn't move after standing up and the chills locked every bone in my body I couldn't breathe. Terrified doesn't cover how afraid I was at that moment. Teeth chattering, fingers rigid, and my back was solid. After moments in this state, I put on layers of sweaters to warm myself. The outside temperature was 65-70*C. So not that bad. I was in shock and not long after putting on my sweaters. My skin felt like it was sun burned and all the weight of the clothing was painful.  I could not lay down, or even roll on my side for rest. Even standing up made my spin hurt.  The muscles in my lower back seized up and the pain was right in the middle of my spin. (The ER Doctors checked and I do not have kidney stones.) I was fighting 99.3+ temp and rising. (This temp is accurate. I have phot evidence.)  There was no sleep that Friday night.  Saturday morning I called the first available chiropractor and went to that appointment at 2pm.  As a new client they don't want to go all out in the first session, but I was in pain with every breathe.  Hyperventilating and over breathing was causing issues with my head and stomach.  The session was amazing, electro therapy mixed with heavy cracks worked on by a professional did help, but only for a brief period of time. Walking away from the building I was still in more pain than ever.  My dad arrived to take me to the ER at roughly 6pm.   Doctors gave me fluid and anti inflammatory drip. Potassium and Tylenol.   It worked. The pain was unreal and I welcomed anything to end the suffering.
LAB_DATA: CT Scan Chest X-Ray Blood Test Urine Test

I am otherwise in excellent health for my age and the only medication taken is Timolol for glaucoma.  I am active and frequently walk several or more miles several days per week.  My reaction seems unusual.  I have only now ceased taking the last of the cataract surgery eye medications, that being Prednisolone eye drops.
