SYMPTOM_TEXT: Felt a bit odd on the couch, little shiver and what felt like adrenaline. I got up and went into the bathroom where the incident occurred. I used to be on 10mg of Ramipril years ago and moved to 5 due to light headedness when standing up. Yellow tinted vision, bright and sparkly. Getting up too fast with heart pressure meds prescribed for albumin /T1D and not for heart pressure. The secondary use of Ramipril is normal for type 1 diabetes after 20+ years. So I went to 5mg and haven?t had that issue since. I should also mention that when this used to happen to me I would lay down and recover with no problem.  Back to the incident it felt exactly like that but on steroids. I was in the bathroom looking for Tylenol and I got light headed, yellow tinted vision, bright and sparkly, ringing in the ears, dizzy, and confused. I remember thinking I should probably get down on the tile floor and lay down like I?m used to from the episodes years ago with 10mg Ramipril causing the same symptoms but never anything so extreme. Next thing I know I?m on the ground waking up where I fainted and hit my head pretty hard on the way down. I probably have a minor concussion. Iced my head in the back where I hit it last night and this morning. Surprisingly 0 bumps, etc other than a little bit sore.  Trying to remember going down is impossible. There is a strange, I guess it?s not strange as I fainted, but to me being 1 moment thinking what I should do then the next moment still thinking that same exact thing but coming to on the bathroom floor with parents yelling over top of me as I was at their house is strange. I recall what almost felt like a dream while I was out but I was wondering why everyone was asking if I was ok, of course I?m ok I thought. Then I realized what happened and crawled around on the floor the rest of the night if I needed anything and was checked every hour through the night which was horrible but necessary.  Also my blood glucose was a 220 at the time of the incident according to my CGM so it didn?t have to do with low blood sugar.  In any case I feel better today but in a fog with a slight headache.
OTHER_MEDS: Ramipril 5mg Fiasp Insulin Medtronic Minmed 670G Continuous Glucose Monitor (CGM) Pepcid 20mg

Saturday, April 3rd, took second dose of Prednisone and continued Benadryl every 4 hours. Symptoms were better in the late morning and early afternoon then started getting worse. Started getting the hives on my arms, legs, and started spreading to my neck, back of my scalp, and onto my face. It got worse at the night progressed and I went to a 24 hours urgent care at 2am on Sunday, April 4th. The doctor checked me out and noting the severe case, increased my prescription to 60mg Prednisone, decreasing 10mg every day, and Famotidine 20mg daily, Clairitin in the morning, and Benadryl at night. Taking the 60mg of Prednisone on April 4th has drastically reduced the symptoms. I will continue the regime to determine if the issue goes away completely.

Pt  sat down at the post vaccine area for the observation, pt stated that 5 mins after getting the vaccine, she felt warm and sweaty and light headed. Pt called the admin staff attention and reported what she is feeling. Staff assisted staff on duty and post vaccine RN checked pt. Staff and RN assisted pt in a laying position on the ground. Initial vitals was checked and recorded as BP 100/70 mmhm; PR 85 ppm; RR 20 cpm; Temp 97.3 F; oxygen sat of 99% at room air.EOA was notified as well and assessed pt.  Pt is alert oriented to self, place, time, location and date. NO Chest pain noted, No SOB noted. quick skin assessment done and no hives or redness noted. Pt was monitored every 15 mins by RN until stable. Pt refused to call 911. Pt was assessed by EOA after 15 mins and pt verbalized feeling better and stated that she had history of being anxious. Pt was gradually transitioned to sitting position. Pt was advised to have someone pick her up but she refused. Pt was also advised to get an appt with primary doctor for follow up check but anything like chest pain or SOB at home to call 911 right away.  Pt was checked once again before discharging pt. Pt is stable and no more complaints of lightheadedness. At 07:28 PM RN accompanied pt to her care. Pt verbalized appreciation and abrupt interventions of her concerns and reaction. EOA made incident report as per protocol.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient got her first 1 of the vaccine and was observed by a nurse for 15 minutes in the observation area.  After 15 minutes she was okay and left. Few minutes after she came back not feeling well. Patient was nauseous, shaking , and feeling week. She was escorted to a stretcher where our nurse started assessing her.  She was given juice and chocolate to raise her blood sugar. EMS arrived at the scene and she underwent further assessments.  Blood sugar was 84 mg/dl and most likely she was hypoglycemic.  Patient was assessed more and she got more time to rest she felt better after some time but she reported she was still week. EMS advised to go to a hospital, but patient refused. Patient said she will be following with her primary care as she's been experiencing similar episodes and to discuss with her doctor if she will be getting a second dose.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: My left arm was sore starting a few minutes after the vaccine. This soreness last through that night. When I woke up the next day, my arm was extremely sore and I was very dizzy. Additionally, my pulse felt fast but my heartbeat seemed to have less strength. My breathing felt more shallow like I wasn't getting as much oxygen from the air that I breathed in as I should. For the first two weeks, the dizziness was very strong. Now, at the three-week mark, it is more manageable and life is somewhat returning to normal. I visited an ENT doctor and their diagnosis was that my dizziness was not being caused by a preexisting medical condition.  Their prediction was that I would be fine, though looking back, I downplayed the severity of my vertigo. At its worst, I felt that, when I went for a walk outside, the surface was the Earth was violently spinning through space, with me stuck to the surface. It felt paralyzing. My body felt almost stuck in shock. I was afraid I would be stuck with this dizziness for the rest of my life since it was so long-lasting. Now, I am taking ginger pills and am watching my sodium intake. I feel better but am extra vigilant about taking ginger and not stressing myself too much. I do not plan on getting a second shot since some of my symptoms mirror those of anaphylaxis.
HISTORY: I had been suffering from a small amount of vertigo. This vertigo was minor and did not interfere with my day-to-day activities.

Experienced brief, minor dizziness about 10 minutes after the shot. On my drive home about 15-20 min. after the shot, I experienced more severe symptoms of anaphylaxis. I was able to breathe but my airway was constricted and swollen. After arriving home, I called pharmacy but their pharmacists were out on lunch. My primary care doctor was closed (Good Friday). I waited until the pharmacist was back from lunch and they advised Benadryl (I took 50 g at 2pm) and to have someone with me for the next 24 hours. Symptoms improved some but by 5pm I still couldn't take a deep breath normally and was concerned about eating food. I went to the ER where they admitted me and administered Pepcid and dexamethasone at 6:22pm. After about an hour and a half, I felt better and was released. Once home, I ate food and that irritated my throat again so I kept an EpiPen nearby that evening just in case. The next morning I felt 100% with no side effects.

My appointment time was 11:20 am on Thursday.  I received the shot about 11:30 am on my upper left arm.  By about 2 pm, I was feeling some soreness and stiffness in my arm.  By about 6pm, the pain in the arm and increased and I was having some loss of range of motion.  I use my computer mouse with my left arm (same as where I got the shot), and I was having trouble moving the mouse.  By 9 pm on the day of the shot, I could not move my arm.  It hung along my left side and would hardly  move more than an inch.  I never lost feeling in that arm, but it wouldn't move. It was as if I'd suffered a stroke.  I had to pick up my left arm with my right arm in order to move it.  For example, in order to undress so I could go to bed, I had to physically lift my left arm and prop it up on a shelf in my bathroom so I could get my sweater off over my head with my right arm.  In addition to loss of all range of motion, I had intense, severe pain in my left arm.  No position was comfortable.  Even lying on my back in bed with my arm at my side made my arm throb horribly.  I usually sleep under a weighted blanket, but I couldn't stand any weight whatsoever on the arm.  The pain (even without the weighted blanket) ran the whole length of my arm, from my shoulder through  my wrist into my fingers.  I'd heard that you shouldn't take anything for pain for the first 24 hours after the shot because it might interfere with the immune reaction, so I didn't take anything.  The next morning (Friday  morning), my arm was still severely painful and unable to be moved.  I couldn't drive because I couldn't lift my left arm enough to grip the steering wheel.  Moving the arm with my right hand still caused horrible pain.  I basically slept or read on the sofa for all of Friday.  By that evening, about 32 hours after the shot, I began to be able to move my left arm a few inches vertically (like a hammer curl) and horizontally (out from my side).  That night, I was able to bear the weight of my weighted blanket on my arm.  By Saturday morning, the pain was drastically reduced.  Saturday morning I could lift my arm to my waist.  By Saturday evening, I could lift my arm to my shoulder.  Sunday I was almost back to normal.  I had only some stiffness and the occasionally twinge if I moved the arm too far too quickly.  I could lift the arm over my head.  Today (Monday), four days after my shot, I still have some mild stiffness, again if I move the arm too quickly.
Left Arm swelling in muscle at injection site  approximately 7 days post  Moderna (mRNA-1273) injection; pain to touch and when lifting arm above head.

Patient received her vaccine at 11:30 AM.  Immediately after receiving the Jansen vaccine, the patient reported feeling lightheaded as she stood up.  She sat in our waiting area for about 10 minutes, and reported that she felt as though her tongue was swelling.  We contacted EMS at this point, and provided a dose of Benadryl to the patient at her request.  We brought the patient into our vaccine room where she began to break out into hives.  She vomited several times.  EMS arrived shortly thereafter and checked to see if the patient was experiencing an allergic reaction.  EMS took the patient to the hospital.  At about 2 PM, the patient called the pharmacy to let us know that she was okay.  She said that it was confirmed as an allergic reaction at the hospital.  She indicated that she had received a steroid injection at the hospital and was feeling much better.  We encouraged the patient to call us at any time if she had any further problems or questions.
LAB_DATA: EMS conducted several tests including blood pressure, pulse, etc.  The patient indicated via phone that several tests were conducted at the hospital as well.
OTHER_MEDS: Unknown, Patient is not a customer at our pharmacy.  We are unaware of other medications/dietary supplements being taken by this particular patient.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Onset of symptoms began at 5:30 PM the day of my vaccination and started with severe aches in my lower back,  a headache  developed within an hour,  by 9:00 PM I was running a low grade fever (100.1) and was feeling nauseous likely because of the developed headache/light sensitivity.   By 9:00 AM on the 4th, I was just feeling lethargic with a bad headache.   All symptoms were gone by 10:30PM on the 4th, the day after I received the vaccination.   There was also injection site pain, but was mostly gone by 4/5.  I began taking Tylenol at 6:30 on the 3rd and was taking it every 4 hours until the evening of the 4th. I also used a heating pad and took an epsom salt bath to help alleviate aches and pains.
Lightheadedness, body aches, chills, headache, slept for 22 hours

On April 3rd at 6:00 am I awoke with difficulty breathing and intense abdominal pain.  Took my eye medicine (Cyproheptadine 4mg) in the morning, difficulty breathing subsided, but abdominal pain remained.  Became lethargic,  noticed a fever around 9:00 am.  Fever was 100 degrees Fahrenheit.  Chills, muscle pains all over body, nausea, inability to eat, acid reflux, temporary loss of feeling in right toes.  Around noon my fever was 102, and my walking heart rate was 146 bpm (according to fitbit sense watch).  I took two Tylenol tablets (recommended dose 2 for adults according to bottle).  Went to urgent care. Fever subsided, and bpm returned to mostly normal.  Blood draw revealed thrombocytopenia.  Platelets were at 72 (units of measurement), normal range is 150-450 (units of measurement).  I was told recommended hospitalization occurs at 50 (units of measurement).  April 4th. Painful abdomen, lack of appetite, nausea, headache. Took 1 Tylenol. Lethargic. Slept most of the day.  Pain behind my eyes. Headache located in front behind both eyes.  Dry throat. Constantly drinking water and Gatorade, Thirsty.  April 5th.  Headache remains. Pain behind eyes remain. Lack of appetite. Planning for second blood draw on April 7th to check Platelets.
OTHER_MEDS: Up and UP Women's Multivitamin Gummies 2 (Regular dose for adults is 2) Cyproheptadine 4mg (for recurring optic neuritis)
HISTORY: Recurring optic Neuritis in right eye.

The pain in those areas intensified to a 10 (on a scale from 1-10) making it impossible to sleep or even move correctly. I was nauseous from the pain which was worse than any pain I have ever felt in my entire life. I developed a severe headache and dry heaves. I could not eat. The next day (4/3) I was able to sleep and I slept all day, rising only to use the toilet and sip water. I had a fever of 100.7. I continued sleeping the rest of the day. When she got her she 2nd immunization on 03/27, a couple days later she developed the same type of rash, only significantly worse.  She denies any difficulty with breathing, swelling of the tongue.  There is no rash throughout the rest the body, she did get the shot in the left shoulder.  She has not had any fevers.  No difficulty breathing.     this rash is consistent with that of shingles.  It occurred on the left shoulder, where the COVID vaccine was given.  She initially developed a rash after the 1st 1, then again after the 2nd shot.  This has pain consistent with that of shingles.  Unlikely allergic reaction, but possible.  She is currently on prednisone she will continue that.  She was given acyclovir and gabapentin.  One dose was given here in the ER.  No swelling of the tongue, no evidence of anaphylaxis.  The rash does not go beyond the left shoulder region.  Patient appears otherwise stable, normal vital signs besides hypertension. SYMPTOM_TEXT: At the time of vaccination, the patient expected to receive the Moderna vaccine for dose 1 of COVID-19 vaccination series. The technician administering the vaccine unknowingly mixed pre-filled syringes of both Pfizer (lot EN6201, exp 6/2021; diluent lot 401817, exp 9/22) and Moderna together in the same container to bring into the vaccination room.  The techinician believed she was providing the Moderna vaccine but unknowingly administered 3 total vaccinations before the mix-up was discovered, and 2 doses of Pfizer vaccine were unaccounted when discovered by the pharmacist on duty. All 3 patients within this time frame of 3 vaccinations given were notified that they potentially received the Pfizer vaccine, as there was no way to confirm with certainty using store camera footage which syringe had definitely been used on each patient.

History of Present Illness    A very pleasant 75yo M who presents to the ED today for evaluation of weakness and left arm pain. He reports that about a month ago, he tripped over his dog and fell, hitting his left shoulder against the box spring on his bed. At the time, he reports he did not have pain in the shoulder, but did have low back pain. He went to his PCP's office on 3/16/21 for evaluation and was not having left shoulder pain at that time; an XR of the lumbar spine was performed which revealed chronic degenerative changes. He was prescribed tramadol and went to PT. Since then, he reports progressive pain in the left shoulder, and gradual loss of mobility in the left shoulder. He also has some swelling in his left hand and wrist. Denies numbness or tingling in the left arm. Today, he was more weak than he has been, and was unable to get up out of bed, so called EMS for assistance. He denies chest pain, dyspnea, cough, headache, lightheadedness or dizziness, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, diarrhea, constipation, recent illness. Reports he has been eating and drinking normally.   His medical history is significant for diabetes mellitus type II, depression, hypothyroidism, hyperlipidemia, OSA on CPAP, morbid obesity with BMI 44, history of PE in 2013 after hernia surgery that was treated with warfarin x 1 year, and history of PSVT s/p ablation in 2013. He received the second dose of his COVID-19 vaccination about a week ago. He tells me he lives at home with his wife, and uses a walker for ambulation for about the past month or so, at the insistence of his daughter after his gait has become increasingly unsteady.   In the ED today, XR of the left shoulder revealed a displaced proximal left humerus fracture. CXR is negative for acute process. Incidentally, he tested positive for COVID-19 today. At approximately 0945 this nurse witnessed patient sitting in the observation area with her head tilted to the left side and her body leaning to the left. The medical assistant was with her holding her body up. Her eyes were closed and she had no color to her face and lips. She was not able to respond to questions being asked. As her head was shaking she was making grunting noises. She was diaphoretic and tremulous. This episode lasted for approximately 60 seconds. Pt then opened her eyes and was able to respond to questions asked but with a delayed response. Pt was moved to the stretcher to lay down. Her color came back to her lips and her blood pressure improved. She was responding to questions appropriately. Pt was diaphoretic for approximately 10 minutes. Ice packs and water were provided. Pt was observed by the medical assistant for 30 minutes. Her HOB was elevated gradually until she was able to dangle her feet and sit on the side of the stretcher.  Pt stated that she was feeling better and was ready to go be with her roommate.    Vital signs were taken and BP 91/54, HR 70, O2 97%.  At 0952 HR was 62. 1005 BP 102/67, HR 57 O2 99%.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 2 weeks after second COVID vaccine,  immediately after taking polyethylene glycol (Miralax) had severe pruritis of bilateral hands and feet with redness of the skin. This passed over the subsequent couple hours then about 6 hours later developed sudden onset severe bilateral conjunctivitis which was so painful I couldn't open my eyes or see very well and ended up going to the ED. Seen by ophthalmology there and told it was likely viral conjunctivitis. Over the next couple hours this passed but then started to develop severe diffuse arthralgias  which lasted about 1 day. This then passed and I felt completely fine. About 2 weeks later I tried taking Miralax again and about 6 hours after taking the Miralax developed the same severe diffuse arthralgias as the prior episode, which again passed in about 1 day. I had taken Miralax several times before getting vaccinated without any issue.

I take sertraline daily and the side effect is rolling nausea. Usually it occurs in the hour or two after taking my daily dose. After the vaccination, the nausea would roll over me in waves at various times all day for the first week.  Nausea is a side effect I was warned about with the vaccine and wanted to report the perceived connection here between the sertraline, worsening nausea and the vaccine dose. Thank you. Moderna administered at 10:30, at 1035 pt was at checkout and started feeling flushed and dizzy, sat down in waiting room, and notified staff  Immediately, 3 nurses attended to pt, brought her to exam room and got her up on exam table. Initial vitals were 180/136, O2 100%, pulse 101. Public safety officer called.  Pt reported itchiness in throat, and epi pen was given to pt, and she self administered dose as at 10:40. Vitals 160/104, 102, 79%, placed on 4L O2 nc. within seconds, pt started feeling better, talking in complete sentences, relaxing, and joking while waiting EMT arrival at 10:49. Vital at 10:55 139/78, 85, O2 100% on 4L. Once pt was sitting on stretched, she started to vomit, and then again became SOB, asking for 2nd epi pen, given to emt and was administered. Then they wheeled pt out to ED.   In ED Note,  Patient is a 40 year old F with PMH multiple allergies, asthma, POTS on metoprolol presenting from clinic after her first dose of Moderna. She states after the injections she felt her throat closing in. She was given an epipen by staff and EMS arrived. She was given another epipen by EMS after she endorsed more throat swelling. EMS reports she did not have any wheezing, stridor, or rashes.    Pt presents to trauma room hyperventillating.   Primary Survey Airway patent speaking clearly w/o stridor breath sounds present bilaterally normal HR and normal BP satting well GCS 15   Lungs are CTAB bilaterally with good movement to the bases and no wheezing. No rashes noted on the skin.    Pt states she felt dizzy with 50mg benadryl. She was also given 125mg solumedrol.    EKG shows sinus tachycardia with HR 108. No STE or TWI.    Plan to observe.    1429  Pt feeling well, has had no respiratory distress. No wheezes noted on repeat eval. Pt has had no wheezing, rashes, or oropharyngeal swelling. Pt states she has epipens for other allergies and will follow up with her PCP. VS remain wnl. Plan to discharge.
OTHER_MEDS: albuterol 90 mcg/ml inhaler Symbicort 160/4.5 cetirizine HCTZ 25 mg daily Keppra 1000 mg BID Metformin 500 mg BID Metoprolol tartarate 25 mg BID Sertraline 25 mg daily
